  {"t":"h2","text":"Getting around"},
  {"t":"p","html":"Falcone–Borsellino airport (Punta Raisi) sits about 35 km from the city center. A train runs direct to Palermo Centrale roughly every 30 minutes, and Prestia e Comandè runs an equivalent bus shuttle if you'd rather go by road. Taxis wait outside arrivals — agree the fare first, and budget 45–60 minutes depending on traffic. Once you're in the historic core, walk: Kalsa, Vucciria, Ballarò, Capo and Quattro Canti all connect on foot, with a free Centro Storico tourist loop bus covering the rest (a 24-hour AMAT ticket runs about €4 if you need the wider bus network)."},
  {"t":"warn","head":"Don't rent a car for the city itself","html":"Wikivoyage flags Palermo driving directly as \"quite dangerous as the rules of the road are not followed.\" Narrow one-way historic-center streets, heavy scooter traffic and chaotic parking make a car more trouble than it's worth inside town — walk or bus centrally, and only rent one for day trips to Cefalù, Segesta or Monreale."},
